Final_exec and Final_Func: UR3 Robotic Arm Image Drawing using Computer Vision and Inverse Kinematics
This project integrates computer vision, coordinate transformations, and robotic manipulation to enable a UR3 robotic arm to autonomously draw an image. The system processes an input image, extracts line features, converts them into world coordinates, and commands the robot arm to trace the image using motion planning and inverse kinematics.
First, computer vision techniques are used to detect line segments from an input image. These pixel coordinates are then transformed from the image coordinate frame to the robot world coordinate frame using a calibrated transformation.
The resulting world coordinates are passed to an inverse kinematics solver that computes the required joint angles for the UR3 manipulator. Using ROS-based control, the robot moves between points and draws the detected line segments sequentially, lifting and lowering the drawing tool when transitioning between separate lines.
The system also includes forward and inverse kinematics models for the UR3 robot based on the product of exponentials formulation, enabling accurate end-effector positioning.
